Problem 1: We derive the probability that a given observation is part of a bootstrap sample. Suppose that we obtain a bootstrap sample from a set of n observations

(a) What is the probability that the first bootstrap observation is not the first observation from the original sample? Justify your answer.

The probability that the first bootstrap observation is not the first observation is \(1 - \dfrac{1}{n}\). This is because the probability of the first bootstrop is \(\dfrac{1}{n}\), therefore, the probability of it not being the first observation would be 1 minus that probability.

(b) What is the probability that the second bootstrap observation is not the first observation from the original sample? Justify your answer.

The probability that the second bootstrap observation is not the first observation is \(1 - \dfrac{1}{n}\). Just like the first bootstrap observation, the probability of the second bootstrap observation is \(\dfrac{1}{n}\), therefore, the probability of it not being the second observation would be 1 minus that probability.

(c) When n = 10, what is the probability that the first observation is in the bootstrap sample?

\(1 - (1 - \dfrac{1}{n})^n\)

\(1 - (1 - \dfrac{1}{10})^{10} = .6513215599\)

(d) When n = 100, what is the probability that the first observation is in the bootstrap sample?

\(1 - (1 - \dfrac{1}{100})^{100} = 0.6339677\)

set.seed(1)

best_tree_size <- cv.apps$size[which.min(cv.apps$dev)]
best_tree_size
## [1] 11

## [1] 0.01557136

The best tree size is 10, and pruning the tree does not change the Test MSE very much. It is 0.0156.
